Interview Questions
1) What is a non-static (instance) block in Java, and when is it executed?
-->👉 A non-static (instance) block in Java is a block of code within a class surrounded by braces {} that runs every time an
    object is created. It acts as an instance initializer, executing after the super constructor but before the constructor of
    the class itself, making it useful for shared initialization logic.
    {
        // instance block
    }
    
    ✔ It runs every time an object is created
    ✔ Executes before the constructor



2) How is a non-static block different from a static block?
-->A non-static (instance) block runs every time an object is instantiated, executing before the constructor to initialize
    instance-specific data. Conversely, a static block runs only once when the class is loaded into memory, initializing 
    class-level data. Static blocks cannot access non-static members directly.

| Feature   | Static Block         | Non-static Block      |
| --------- | -------------------- | --------------------- |
| Keyword   | `static`             | No keyword            |
| Execution | Once (class loading) | Every object creation |
| Memory    | Method Area          | Method Area           |
| Use       | Class-level init     | Object-level init     |


3) When is a non-static block executed in relation to the constructor?
-->A non-static (instance) block is executed every time an object is created, immediately after the constructor's call to super() and before 
    the constructor's own body logic runs. It acts as an initializer shared among all constructors, running after static blocks
    but before the constructor executes
    class Test {
        {
            System.out.println("Block");
        }
    
        Test() {
            System.out.println("Constructor");
        }
    }


4) Can we have multiple non-static blocks in the same class? If yes, in what order do they execute?
-->Yes, we can have multiple non-static (instance) blocks in a class.
    👉 They execute:
    In the order they are written in the class (top → bottom)
    Before the constructor
    Every time an object is created
    
    Example:
    
    class Test {
        {
            System.out.println("Block 1");
        }
    
        {
            System.out.println("Block 2");
        }
    
        Test() {
            System.out.println("Constructor");
        }
    }
    
    Output:
    
    Block 1
    Block 2
    Constructor



5) Can a non-static block access static and non-static variables? Explain.
-->✅ Yes, it can access both.
    👉 Because:
    It is executed during object creation
    At that time, both:
    static variables (class-level)
    non-static variables (instance-level)
    are available
    
    Example:
    
    class Demo {
        static int a = 10;
        int b = 20;
    
        {
            System.out.println(a); // static
            System.out.println(b); // non-static
        }
    }




6) Can a non-static block call methods (both static and non-static)?
-->✅ Yes, it can call both.

        👉 Reason:
        
        It behaves like part of the object initialization process
        So it has access to everything the object has
        
        Example:
        
        class Demo {
            static void show1() {
                System.out.println("Static method");
            }
        
            void show2() {
                System.out.println("Non-static method");
            }
        
            {
                show1();
                show2();
            }
        }



7) What happens if both a parent and child class have non-static blocks? In which order are they executed
during object creation?
-->👉 Execution order during object creation:

    Parent class non-static blocks
    Parent constructor
    Child class non-static blocks
    Child constructor
    📌 Always remember: Parent → Child
    Example:
    class Parent {
        {
            System.out.println("Parent Block");
        }
        Parent() {
            System.out.println("Parent Constructor");
        }
    }
    
    class Child extends Parent {
        {
            System.out.println("Child Block");
        }
    
        Child() {
            System.out.println("Child Constructor");
        }
    }
    
    Output:
    Parent Block
    Parent Constructor
    Child Block
    Child Constructor





8) Can we use the this keyword inside a non-static block? Why or why not?
-->✅ Yes, we can use this.
    
    👉 Because:
    
    Non-static block is executed in instance context
    this refers to the current object
    
    Example:
    
    class Demo {
        int x = 10;
    
        {
            System.out.println(this.x);
        }
    }



9) Can a non-static block throw exceptions or use try–catch?
-->✅ Yes, it can.
    👉 You can:
    Use try–catch
    Throw exceptions
    Example:
    
    class Demo {
        {
            try {
                int x = 10 / 0;
            } catch (Exception e) {
                System.out.println("Exception handled");
            }
        }
    } 
    ⚠️ If you throw a checked exception, it must be handled inside the block (since constructors don’t declare it automatically).




10) What is the real purpose of using non-static blocks in Java programs (practical use cases)?
-->👉 In real-world projects, non-static blocks are rarely used, but they exist for:
        
        🔹 Common practical uses:
        Code that must run before every constructor
        Shared initialization logic across multiple constructors
        Reducing duplicate code
        🔹 Example use case:
        class Student {
            int id;
        
            {
                System.out.println("Common initialization");
            }
        
            Student() {
                System.out.println("Default constructor");
            }
        
            Student(int id) {
                this.id = id;
                System.out.println("Parameterized constructor");
            }
        }
        
        👉 Here, the block runs for both constructors, avoiding repetition.



    ✅ Final Interview Tip
    👉 If asked in interview:
    Say:
    "Non-static blocks are mainly used for common initialization logic, but in modern Java, constructors or helper methods are preferred for
    better readability."
